    "recap_url": "https://www.emueagles.com/news/2026/3/13/baseball-drops-series-opening-offensive-thriller-at-ball-state",
    "recap_headline": "Eastern Michigan Athletics",
    "recap_text": "MUNCIE, Ind. (EMUEagles.com) --\nThe Eastern Michigan University baseball team dropped an explosive Mid-American Conference series opener to Ball State University, 17-13, Friday, March 13, at Shebek Stadium.\nEastern set multiple offensive season highs, marking its best offensive showing of the 2026 campaign. The contest saw a total of 30 runs off 33 hits, with Eastern totaling 15 knocks and the Cardinals earning 18.\nEMU got off to a 12-9 lead after four innings but was outscored 8-1 over the final five innings. Ball State's John Chambers (2-3) was credited with the win, and Eastern junior\nCole Egan\n(Pittsburgh, Pa./West Allegheny/George Mason)\n(1-1) was tagged with the loss.\nHow it Happened\nEastern Michigan's offense surged early, racing out to an 8-3 lead after two innings behind timely hitting and aggressive baserunning.\nNathan Borchardt\n(Stanley, N.C./East Lincoln/King)\nsparked the attack with an RBI double in the first and added a sacrifice fly in the second.\nThe Eagles' six-run second inning was highlighted by a two-run single from\nTy Stecko\n(North Huntingdon, Pa./Norwin/Mount St. Mary's)\nand an RBI single by\nBruce Jellison\n(Hartland, Mich./Hartland/Wabash Valley)\n, capitalizing on two Ball State errors for additional runs.\nThe Cardinals reclaimed the lead in the fifth, scoring four runs off a mix of extra-base hits and Eagle errors to go up 13-12. Despite a two-run home run from\nBen Schechterman\n(Aurora, Ohio/Aurora/Ohio State)\nin the fourth, his first career blast.\nBall State went on to outscore the Eagles 8-1 in the final five innings to secure a 17-13 series-opening win.\nGame Notes\n\u00bb Eastern's record went to 4-14 (0-4 MAC) and Ball State's improved to 8-8 (3-1 MAC).\n\u00bb EMU set a season high with 15 hits, marking the third time it has eclipsed 10 hits this season.\n\u00bb The Eagles' 13 runs mark a season-high and the second time it has put up double-digit runs this season, as it holds a 1-1 record in such games.\n\u00bb Eastern's 13 runs and 15 hits both rank fifth in the MAC in a single game this season.\n\u00bb Eastern's 10 RBI stand as its second-highest total of the season after driving in 11 in an 11-6 win at Little Rock, Feb. 14. Friday's game marked the second time EMU has totaled double-digit RBI as it lost for the first time when doing so.\n\u00bb The Eagles totaled six extra-base hits (four doubles, two home runs), tying their season-high after knocking six against the RedHawks, March 8.\n\u00bb Eastern plated six runs in the second inning for its third inning with four or more runs this season. EMU's six runs in the second are its second-highest single-inning total after scoring eight runs in the seventh inning in an 11-6 win at Little Rock, Feb. 14.\n\u00bb\nTJ Williams\n(Racine, Wis./Racine Horlick/Kansas)\nrecorded his team-high fifth multi-hit game of the season as he went 2-for-2 with three runs scored and reached on all three plate appearances.\n\u00bb\nNathan Borchardt\nsecured his fourth multi-hit game of the season as he batted 3-for-5 with a pair of doubles and two RBI. The game went down as his second of the season with multiple RBI. His two extra-base hits tied a season high.\n\u00bb\nDevan Zirwas\n(Imperial, Pa./West Allegheny/VCU)\ntied his season high with three hits, marking his third game with multiple hits this season. He drove in a pair of runs for his team-high fifth game with multiple RBI this season. He leads the Eagles with 17 RBI and 11 extra-base hits in 2026.\n\u00bb\nTy Stecko\ntotaled two RBI for his fourth multi-RBI outing. He's up to 13 RBI this season, ranking second on the team.\n\u00bb\nBen Schechterman\n(Aurora, Ohio/Aurora/Ohio State)\nsmashed his first career home run over the right-center wall for a two-run shot in the fourth inning. Schechterman drove in multiple runs for the first time this season and the second of his career. He earned his first multi-hit game of the season after singling in the top of the sixth.\n\u00bb\nTristan Crane\n(Berkley, Mich./Brother Rice/Texas A&M Corpus Christi)\ntallied his first long ball of the season with a solo bomb to right field in the ninth inning. Crane's homer went down as Eastern's 20th of the year, ranking second in the MAC.\nHistorical Notes\n\u00bb The Eagles and Cardinals met for the 176th time. Eastern holds an 85-91-1 all-time record against Ball State and a 13-31 mark since 1999 when facing it in Muncie.\nUp Next\nEastern Michigan continues its MAC series at Ball State Saturday, March 14. First pitch is scheduled for 1 p.m. at Shebek Stadium in Muncie, Ind.\nFollow Us\nKeep up with all things Eastern baseball by following the team on X\n@EMU_Baseball\n, and on Instagram\n@emu_baseball\n."
